{"text": " You drop your clothes into a Decathlon checkout bin and it instantly calculates your total. No barcodes. How? It uses radio-frequency identification. If you peel back the layers of a Decathlon price tag, you won't just find paper. You'll find a microscopic computer chip attached to a flat, squiggly, aluminum antenna. Notice, there is no battery. So how does it turn on? When you drop your clothes into the bin, an RFID reader hidden inside the walls blasts an invisible radio wave. Through a process called electromagnetic induction, the aluminum antenna catches that wave and physically converts it into a tiny spark of electricity. That brief spark wakes up the microchip. The chip instantly uses the exact same energy to bounce back its electronic product code. This isn't a generic barcode, it is a precise serial number that says, blue t-shirt, size medium, exact item number 4902115, it is completely unique in the world. The radar organizes the signals, matches those unique IDs to the database and calculates your total in milliseconds. Follow for more system architecture.", "segments": [{"id": 0, "seek": 0, "start": 0.0, "end": 5.32, "text": " You drop your clothes into a Decathlon checkout bin and it instantly calculates your total.", "tokens": [50364, 509, 3270, 428, 5534, 666, 257, 12427, 41269, 37153, 5171, 293, 309, 13518, 4322, 1024, 428, 3217, 13, 50670], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.22581444897697966, "compression_ratio": 1.4959677419354838, "no_speech_prob": 0.030798517167568207, "words": [{"word": " You", "start": 0.0, "end": 0.46, "probability": 0.5979455709457397}, {"word": " drop", "start": 0.46, "end": 0.84, "probability": 0.9810429811477661}, {"word": " your", "start": 0.84, "end": 1.06, "probability": 0.9913996458053589}, {"word": " clothes", "start": 1.06, "end": 1.44, "probability": 0.6690003871917725}, {"word": " into", "start": 1.44, "end": 1.78, "probability": 0.9579877257347107}, {"word": " a", "start": 1.78, "end": 1.94, "probab